1
00:00:14,960 --> 00:00:17,327
[man] Toby!

2
00:00:17,428 --> 00:00:19,793
Toby Tyler!

3
00:00:23,563 --> 00:00:25,562
Toby.

4
00:00:27,598 --> 00:00:30,197
Where are you?

5
00:00:33,099 --> 00:00:34,998
Toby.

6
00:00:38,000 --> 00:00:40,500
Toby Tyler.

7
00:00:45,600 --> 00:00:48,921
[brass band playing]

8
00:01:25,778 --> 00:01:28,038
[crowd cheering]

9
00:01:37,475 --> 00:01:40,124
[roaring]

10
00:01:43,200 --> 00:01:46,980
[monkeys screeching]

11
00:01:57,320 --> 00:02:00,255
Stand back, please.
Make way for the elephants.

12
00:02:00,357 --> 00:02:04,325
Make way for the elephants.
Look out there.
This is dangerous.

13
00:02:04,427 --> 00:02:07,028
- Stand back.
Stand back, please.
- [laughing]

14
00:02:07,130 --> 00:02:09,899
Make way for the elephants.

15
00:03:04,553 --> 00:03:06,921
[roaring]

16
00:03:30,811 --> 00:03:35,081
[calliope playing]

17
00:04:07,545 --> 00:04:12,350
[man] Here you are, ladies and
gents. Get a cane, get a whip.

18
00:04:12,451 --> 00:04:17,322
One cent, and here's
a balloon for you.
Just a penny, a copper penny.

19
00:04:17,422 --> 00:04:21,326
Balloons here.
One penny. One copper penny.

20
00:04:21,426 --> 00:04:24,496
- Balloons here...
- [man] Get your tickets
for the show.

21
00:04:24,596 --> 00:04:27,197
My balloon.
I want to get another balloon.

22
00:04:27,299 --> 00:04:30,735
[man] Balloons here,
all kinds, all colors...

23
00:04:32,604 --> 00:04:34,505
Step right in
and enjoy the show.

24
00:04:34,606 --> 00:04:36,741
Hurry, now. Step in
and enjoy the show.

25
00:04:36,842 --> 00:04:40,011
Hurry, hurry, hurry.
Are you going in?

26
00:04:40,112 --> 00:04:41,778
No, sir.

27
00:04:41,880 --> 00:04:43,981
Step in and enjoy
the show, gentlemen.

28
00:04:44,082 --> 00:04:47,484
[man] There you are,
little lady, and thank you,
madam, very much.

29
00:04:47,585 --> 00:04:50,520
Ladies and gentlemen, step right
up. Fresh-roasted peanuts.

30
00:04:50,621 --> 00:04:55,392
Peanuts, popcorn,
candied apples and taffy,
all fresh and delicious.

31
00:04:55,493 --> 00:04:57,594
All right, folks,
step right up here.

32
00:04:57,695 --> 00:05:02,133
The peanuts are grown
on the plantation and roasted
here on the premises.

33
00:05:03,701 --> 00:05:05,569
Are you a looker
or a buyer?

34
00:05:05,670 --> 00:05:08,672
About how many peanuts would you
say I could get for a penny?

35
00:05:08,772 --> 00:05:12,375
In the normal course
of business, I don't
sell them by the penny.

36
00:05:12,476 --> 00:05:14,544
- [sighing] Oh.
- However,

37
00:05:14,645 --> 00:05:17,747
seeing as you're a handsome
young rooster with cash in hand,

38
00:05:17,848 --> 00:05:20,050
I devise I might
part with, say,

39
00:05:20,150 --> 00:05:23,019
oh, six genuine plantation-grown
Georgie goobers.

40
00:05:23,120 --> 00:05:24,286
Six?

41
00:05:24,388 --> 00:05:26,722
It's more than
if you bought them by the bag.

42
00:05:26,823 --> 00:05:29,525
That's a solemn fact.

43
00:05:30,193 --> 00:05:32,360
Here.

44
00:05:43,807 --> 00:05:46,575
Folks, step up.
It's all fresh and
it's all refreshing.

45
00:05:46,676 --> 00:05:49,745
Nice and cold and refreshing.
Plantation peanuts.

46
00:05:49,845 --> 00:05:51,747
Do you swap the ones
that are bad?

47
00:05:51,847 --> 00:05:55,883
Bad? I don't vend bad peanuts
in my establishment, boy.

48
00:05:55,985 --> 00:06:01,190
Maybe a little underbred,
perhaps timeworn,
but not really bad.

49
00:06:02,124 --> 00:06:04,458
Tastes bad.

50
00:06:04,559 --> 00:06:07,561
Here's two more. Run along,
or you'll miss the best part.

51
00:06:07,662 --> 00:06:10,164
- Oh, I'm not going.
- Not going?

52
00:06:10,266 --> 00:06:12,499
Ah, you lack
the price of a ticket.

53
00:06:12,601 --> 00:06:13,968
Yes, sir.

54
00:06:14,068 --> 00:06:17,138
I suppose your parents
are bringing you tonight.

55
00:06:17,239 --> 00:06:19,573
No, sir, I don't
have any parents.

56
00:06:23,477 --> 00:06:25,847
Orphan boy, eh?

57
00:06:25,948 --> 00:06:29,482
Well, have you ever thought
of joining the circus, lad?

58
00:06:29,583 --> 00:06:31,218
Me?

59
00:06:31,319 --> 00:06:35,155
Imagine, being a part of
the glorious confraternity
of the big top.

60
00:06:35,256 --> 00:06:36,824
That company of artistes

61
00:06:36,924 --> 00:06:39,725
who travel
the length and breadth
of this great land of ours.

62
00:06:39,828 --> 00:06:43,463
- How would you like that?
- But what could I do?

63
00:06:43,564 --> 00:06:46,800
You could become...

64
00:06:48,602 --> 00:06:50,170
...a concessionaire.

65
00:06:50,270 --> 00:06:51,939
I could?

66
00:06:54,374 --> 00:06:56,643
- A con...
- ...cessionaire.

67
00:06:56,744 --> 00:06:59,980
Rolls out on the tongue
mighty important, don't it, boy?

68
00:07:00,081 --> 00:07:02,547
- Yes, sir.
- Free transportation,

69
00:07:02,650 --> 00:07:06,218
snug place to sleep,
all you can eat,
see the performance anytime,

70
00:07:06,319 --> 00:07:08,353
rub shoulders with the great
and near great.

71
00:07:08,455 --> 00:07:11,923
And if that weren't enough,
each and every Saturday night

72
00:07:12,025 --> 00:07:14,193
yours truly, Harry Tupper,

73
00:07:14,294 --> 00:07:16,461
will present you...

74
00:07:17,429 --> 00:07:18,831
...with one of these.

75
00:07:18,932 --> 00:07:21,167
What do you say, lad?
Is it a bargain?

76
00:07:21,268 --> 00:07:26,272
I'd like that better
than anything else
in the whole world.

77
00:07:26,372 --> 00:07:28,873
You would, eh?

78
00:07:28,975 --> 00:07:32,978
The only trouble is Uncle Daniel
and Aunt Olive need me.

79
00:07:34,580 --> 00:07:37,116
Aunt and uncle?

80
00:07:37,217 --> 00:07:41,552
They're awful poor,
and there's lots of work
for me around the farm.

81
00:07:41,653 --> 00:07:44,055
I understand.
It does you credit.

82
00:07:44,156 --> 00:07:47,024
I'm a loyal man myself,
and I love to see it in others.

83
00:07:47,127 --> 00:07:49,660
- I could ask them.
- Don't give it another thought.

84
00:07:49,762 --> 00:07:51,896
I'll just pick up a boy
in the next town.

85
00:07:51,997 --> 00:07:54,464
Plenty would be glad
for such an opportunity.

86
00:07:54,566 --> 00:07:57,236
Yes, sir.
Anyway, thank you.

87
00:07:59,771 --> 00:08:01,973
Wait a minute.
Come here.

88
00:08:04,508 --> 00:08:07,712
Just so's you and I part
the best of friends,

89
00:08:07,812 --> 00:08:10,647
here's a free pass
for tonight's performance.

90
00:08:10,749 --> 00:08:13,851
- But Mr. Tupper...
- Bring a friend
and enjoy yourself.

91
00:08:13,952 --> 00:08:17,421
Courtesy of yours truly,
Harry Tupper.

92
00:08:17,521 --> 00:08:20,090
- Mr. Tupper...
- Farewell. Ice-cold lemonade.

93
00:08:20,191 --> 00:08:22,125
It's pink, it's cold,
it's refreshing.

94
00:08:22,227 --> 00:08:27,196
[Tupper] Ice-cold lemonade.
Pink and refreshing.
Ice-cold lemonade.

95
00:08:38,442 --> 00:08:41,344
Hey, Red.
Red, look at what I've got here.

96
00:08:41,444 --> 00:08:42,879
Look, Red.

97
00:08:42,981 --> 00:08:44,481
Guess what this is.

98
00:08:44,581 --> 00:08:48,485
A genuine free pass
to the circus. Look.

99
00:08:48,585 --> 00:08:51,487
- [whinnies]
- Yahoo!

100
00:08:59,129 --> 00:09:01,264
Where have you been?

101
00:09:02,565 --> 00:09:06,468
I said where have you been?

102
00:09:06,569 --> 00:09:08,604
Answer me.

103
00:09:08,705 --> 00:09:10,538
I'm sorry, Uncle Daniel.

104
00:09:10,640 --> 00:09:14,710
I meant to come right back,
but there was a parade.

105
00:09:14,810 --> 00:09:17,779
And then I happened to go
by the circus grounds,

106
00:09:17,880 --> 00:09:19,680
and a man gave me a free pass.

107
00:09:19,782 --> 00:09:22,184
- Look.
- Circus?

108
00:09:22,285 --> 00:09:24,419
Did you know the hogs
broke the fence down

109
00:09:24,519 --> 00:09:28,124
because you didn't feed them
and rooted up the turnip field?

110
00:09:28,224 --> 00:09:30,557
Toby, we'd counted on
selling that crop.

111
00:09:30,659 --> 00:09:32,961
You know how we need money
in the house.

112
00:09:33,061 --> 00:09:36,965
- You're a shiftless,
ungrateful boy.
- Don't be hard on him.

113
00:09:37,065 --> 00:09:39,934
Boys get skittish
when a circus comes to town.

114
00:09:40,035 --> 00:09:42,803
He don't have a right
to behave like other boys.

115
00:09:42,905 --> 00:09:44,571
He's got no rights at all.

116
00:09:44,673 --> 00:09:47,141
- And he knows why.
- Don't say that to him.

117
00:09:47,243 --> 00:09:50,378
I'm a poor man, yet I took you
in out of decency's sake

118
00:09:50,478 --> 00:09:53,579
- when no one else
would have you.
- Daniel.

119
00:09:53,682 --> 00:09:58,552
I don't see why we didn't
send you to the county home
in the first place.

120
00:09:58,653 --> 00:10:02,522
You're no kin to us.
You're nothing to us.

121
00:10:02,623 --> 00:10:06,026
Nothin' but a millstone
around our necks.

122
00:10:06,126 --> 00:10:08,862
You don't mean that, Daniel.

123
00:10:10,130 --> 00:10:12,266
You just go up to bed
and stay there.

124
00:10:12,367 --> 00:10:15,534
There'll be no place
at supper for you.

125
00:10:35,922 --> 00:10:38,357
Those were cruel things to say.

126
00:10:38,459 --> 00:10:40,926
Get on with the supper, Olive.

127
00:10:42,963 --> 00:10:44,830
[man] Hurry it up, Tupper.

128
00:10:44,931 --> 00:10:49,901
- This wagon's already loaded.
- [man #2] Gangway.
Horses coming through.

129
00:10:50,004 --> 00:10:53,805
- [man] Giddyup.
- [man #2] Move those
stringers out.

130
00:10:55,408 --> 00:10:57,143
Guy out over here.

131
00:10:57,243 --> 00:11:00,878
Men, guy out!
Over here!

132
00:11:00,981 --> 00:11:02,680
[Toby] Mr. Tupper?

133
00:11:04,750 --> 00:11:07,319
Mr. Tupper?

134
00:11:07,419 --> 00:11:10,755
- Here I am, Mr. Tupper.
- Well, what of it?

135
00:11:10,855 --> 00:11:13,457
Don't you remember me,
Mr. Tupper?

136
00:11:14,494 --> 00:11:17,262
- You said I could work for you.
- So?

137
00:11:18,597 --> 00:11:22,100
- I'm ready.
- [man] Move it, move it!

138
00:11:22,201 --> 00:11:24,502
What about
that aunt and uncle?

139
00:11:24,603 --> 00:11:28,439
Well, it's all right.
They don't want me.

140
00:11:28,539 --> 00:11:31,542
They said I was a millstone
around their necks.

141
00:11:33,512 --> 00:11:35,612
All right,
you got the job.

142
00:11:35,713 --> 00:11:39,350
- Fifty cents a week.
- Today you said a dollar.

143
00:11:39,451 --> 00:11:41,984
If Harry Tupper said a dollar,
he meant a dollar.

144
00:11:42,087 --> 00:11:46,223
But don't let me catch you
running away once I teach you
the business.

145
00:11:46,324 --> 00:11:48,959
- It takes a lot out of me, boy.
- No, sir.

146
00:11:51,062 --> 00:11:54,331
Gentlemen's agreement.

147
00:11:54,433 --> 00:11:57,301
It's one of the most solemn
things there is. Understand?

148
00:11:57,401 --> 00:12:00,470
- Yes, sir.
- You stay here and
stay out of trouble.

149
00:12:00,571 --> 00:12:02,306
I'll be right back.

150
00:12:02,407 --> 00:12:04,140
- Mr. Tupper?
- Yes?

151
00:12:04,241 --> 00:12:06,310
- I'm hungry.
- So?

152
00:12:06,411 --> 00:12:10,347
I didn't have anything
to eat for supper.

153
00:12:10,448 --> 00:12:13,916
[sighing]
All right.

154
00:12:14,017 --> 00:12:17,652
[man]
Throw a blanket over the him!
He's coming down with a cold!

155
00:12:17,754 --> 00:12:20,890
There you are, my boy.
Nutritional gold
from the Indies.

156
00:12:20,990 --> 00:12:24,561
- See that it lasts you
till morning.
- Yes, sir.

157
00:12:24,661 --> 00:12:27,197
- [man] Give us
a hand, will you?
- [man #2] Up.

158
00:12:27,297 --> 00:12:28,664
[man] Olie!

159
00:12:28,764 --> 00:12:31,700
- [man #2] Chuck wagon ready.
- [man #3] Pull that back.

160
00:12:31,801 --> 00:12:34,769
[man #3] Get some of this stuff
back in there.

161
00:12:34,870 --> 00:12:37,706
- [man] We're leavin', boys.
- [man #2] Lift it up.

162
00:12:39,342 --> 00:12:42,744
- [man shouting]
- Steady up, boys. Steady.

163
00:12:42,845 --> 00:12:45,647
Steady!

164
00:12:45,748 --> 00:12:48,283
[horse whinnying]

165
00:12:49,318 --> 00:12:51,720
[man]
Clear that... [indistinct]

166
00:12:53,255 --> 00:12:54,990
Hey!

167
00:12:58,327 --> 00:12:59,994
What are you doing?

168
00:13:04,366 --> 00:13:08,570
- Give that back, you thief!
- [screeching]

169
00:13:11,373 --> 00:13:14,808
[monkey screeching]

170
00:13:14,908 --> 00:13:17,646
What's going on?
What did you do to that chimp?

171
00:13:17,746 --> 00:13:21,581
Me? I didn't do a thing.
He stole my banana.

172
00:13:21,684 --> 00:13:24,185
[screeching]

173
00:13:25,586 --> 00:13:28,456
All right, troublemaker.
Settle down.

174
00:13:28,556 --> 00:13:32,259
Now, as for you,
you'd better get home.

175
00:13:33,127 --> 00:13:35,196
I told you
to stay out of trouble.

176
00:13:35,297 --> 00:13:37,664
He stole my banana.

177
00:13:39,500 --> 00:13:43,036
- What's wrong here?
- I-I-I... Nothing, Colonel,
nothing at all.

178
00:13:43,136 --> 00:13:45,239
The chimp just got
a little excited.

179
00:13:45,340 --> 00:13:48,475
- Who's this?
- This is my new helper, sir.

180
00:13:48,575 --> 00:13:51,911
- Picking them small,
aren't you?
- Well, sir...

181
00:13:53,481 --> 00:13:55,214
He has no folks,
the poor lad,

182
00:13:55,317 --> 00:13:58,851
and I thought I'd take him
under my wing and give him
a helping hand.

183
00:13:58,952 --> 00:14:01,353
Spare me your
kind intentions, Tupper.

184
00:14:01,455 --> 00:14:04,690
Get these wagons moving.
The boy can ride
up top with Ben.

185
00:14:04,792 --> 00:14:06,592
Thunderation, Colonel.

186
00:14:06,693 --> 00:14:09,395
Why pick me to wet-nurse
Tupper's sniveling brats?

187
00:14:09,497 --> 00:14:12,899
Trim your wagon, Ben.
We're moving.

188
00:14:13,000 --> 00:14:16,734
Olie, get these sideboards up.

189
00:14:18,737 --> 00:14:21,507
- Mr. Tupper?
- Hmm?

190
00:14:21,608 --> 00:14:23,609
I kind of changed my mind.

191
00:14:23,710 --> 00:14:26,345
Oh, now, lad.

192
00:14:26,446 --> 00:14:30,248
Listen. Don't you worry none
about our rough ways. No, sir.

193
00:14:30,350 --> 00:14:33,819
We don't mean a thing by it.
Not a blessed thing. No, no.

194
00:14:33,920 --> 00:14:36,589
Here, look. Look what
Mr. Tupper has here for you.

195
00:14:36,689 --> 00:14:40,092
There's a bag for you
of peppermint jaws.

196
00:14:40,192 --> 00:14:42,426
That should last you
till morning.

197
00:14:47,966 --> 00:14:51,068
All right, now, lad.
Right up this ladder here.

198
00:14:51,169 --> 00:14:54,272
I'll take that for you.
You'll be snug
as a mouse up there.

199
00:14:54,372 --> 00:14:56,841
Mr. Cotter will
take good care of you.

200
00:15:02,281 --> 00:15:05,815
[man] All right, keep them cats
covered when you move 'em!

201
00:15:08,519 --> 00:15:11,921
Colonel Castle says you ride
with me, you ride.

202
00:15:12,022 --> 00:15:15,091
Get a tight tailhold
on yourself, sonny.

203
00:15:15,192 --> 00:15:18,229
Bess, Will, ha!

204
00:15:19,564 --> 00:15:21,732
Get. Giddap.

205
00:15:29,006 --> 00:15:30,741
Let's get
one thing straight.

206
00:15:30,841 --> 00:15:32,608
Me, I don't like kids.

207
00:15:32,710 --> 00:15:36,747
Especially runaways.
They're a weak-livered lot.

208
00:15:36,846 --> 00:15:41,684
Kid has a good home.
First time something
goes wrong, he runs away.

209
00:15:41,786 --> 00:15:44,587
Then he finds things
don't suit him just right.

210
00:15:44,688 --> 00:15:47,222
He wants to run
back home again.

211
00:15:52,228 --> 00:15:55,129
Go ahead. Jump.
Nobody'll miss you.

212
00:15:55,231 --> 00:15:57,966
I doubt you're worth missing.

213
00:15:58,067 --> 00:16:00,102
Jump. Don't be scared.

214
00:16:00,203 --> 00:16:03,272
I'm not scared.

215
00:16:04,408 --> 00:16:06,875
And I'm not scared
of you either.

216
00:16:07,977 --> 00:16:10,244
Fair enough, sonny.

217
00:16:10,347 --> 00:16:13,648
My name isn't Sonny.
It's Toby Tyler.

218
00:16:13,749 --> 00:16:16,618
All right, sonny.
We'll call you Toby.

219
00:16:16,720 --> 00:16:19,688
Now, it's none
of my business, Toby,

220
00:16:19,789 --> 00:16:21,923
but maybe you better
catch some sleep.

221
00:16:22,024 --> 00:16:23,792
Morning comes early
with this outfit.

222
00:16:23,891 --> 00:16:26,894
- I'm not sleepy.
- Suit yourself.

223
